# 🔹 What is Algorithm Analysis?

Algorithm Analysis is the study of:

✅ Running Time
✅ Memory Usage
✅ Scalability

Purpose:

To compare algorithms independent of hardware.

---

# 🔹 Why Complexity Matters?

Suppose two algorithms solve the same problem.

### Algorithm A

[
O(n)
]

### Algorithm B

[
O(n^2)
]

For:

[
n=100000
]

Algorithm A is dramatically faster.

📌 GATE focuses on growth rate, not actual execution time.

---

# 🔹 Time Complexity

Measures how running time grows with input size.

Input size:

[
n
]

---

### Example

```c
for(i=0;i<n;i++)
{
   printf("%d",i);
}
```

Runs n times.

Complexity:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Space Complexity

Extra memory used by algorithm.

Example:

```c
int arr[n];
```

Space:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Asymptotic Notations

---

# 1️⃣ Big-O Notation

Upper Bound

Represents worst-case growth.

Example:

[
3n^2+2n+5
]

becomes:

[
O(n^2)
]

Reason:

Highest-order term dominates.

---

# 2️⃣ Big-Ω (Omega)

Lower Bound

Represents best-case growth.

Example:

Linear Search:

Best Case:

[
\Omega(1)
]

Element found at first position.

---

# 3️⃣ Big-Θ (Theta)

Tight Bound

When upper and lower bounds match.

Example:

[
3n+5
]

[
\Theta(n)
]

---

📌 Very common GATE theory question.

---

# 🔹 Complexity Growth Order

From fastest to slowest:

[
O(1)
<
O(\log n)
<
O(n)
<
O(n\log n)
<
O(n^2)
<
O(n^3)
<
O(2^n)
<
O(n!)
]

📌 Must memorize.

