# 🔹 Recurrence Relations

Used for recursive algorithms.

---

### Example 1

```text
T(n)=T(n−1)+1
```

Expansion:

```text
T(n)
=T(n−2)+2
=T(n−3)+3
...
```

Result:

[
O(n)
]

---

### Example 2

Binary Search

```text
T(n)=T(n/2)+1
```

Result:

[
O(\log n)
]

---

### Example 3

Merge Sort

```text
T(n)=2T(n/2)+n
```

Result:

[
O(n\log n)
]

---

# 🔹 Master Theorem (VERY IMPORTANT)

General form:

[
T(n)=aT(n/b)+f(n)
]

Where:

* a = number of subproblems
* b = size reduction factor

---

### Case 1

If

[
f(n)=O(n^{\log_b a-\epsilon})
]

Then:

[
T(n)=\Theta(n^{\log_b a})
]

---

### Case 2

If

[
f(n)=\Theta(n^{\log_b a})
]

Then:

[
T(n)=\Theta(n^{\log_b a}\log n)
]

---

### Case 3

If

[
f(n)=\Omega(n^{\log_b a+\epsilon})
]

Then:

[
T(n)=\Theta(f(n))
]

---

📌 GATE frequently asks direct Master Theorem questions.

---

# 🔹 Example Using Master Theorem

Find:

[
T(n)=2T(n/2)+n
]

Here:

[
a=2,\ b=2
]

[
n^{\log_2 2}=n
]

Case 2 applies.

Answer:

[
O(n\log n)
]

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

Ignore constants.

[
100n = O(n)
]

---

### Trap 2

Ignore lower-order terms.

[
n^2+n = O(n^2)
]

---

### Trap 3

Nested loops do NOT always mean (O(n^2)).

Depends on loop bounds.

---

### Trap 4

Binary Search is:

[
O(\log n)
]

not

[
O(n)
]

